# Vault Memory

- Treat `docs/` as the durable project memory and Obsidian vault.
- Canonical workflow: `docs/90-Meta/agent-memory-protocol.md`. Governance
  (memory classes, canonical-location rule, supersede discipline,
  entry-point conformance): `docs/90-Meta/vault-governance.md`. This rule is an
  orchestrator; if it disagrees with those notes, the vault wins.
- Session start: read `docs/00-Index/Agent-Onboarding.md`, then
  `docs/00-Index/Current-State.md`, then relevant maps, accepted ADRs, approved
  specs, and the latest `docs/40-Execution/session-handoffs/*` if continuing.
- Use the `vault-memory` skill (`.cursor/skills/vault-memory/SKILL.md`) for the
  repeatable start/update/wrap-up checklist.
- Prefer `current`, `accepted`, `approved` notes. Never implement from `draft`,
  `superseded`, or `archived` notes.
- `draft`/`idea` notes are the recognized intent layer: read for direction and
  to avoid re-deciding, but do not implement from or cite them as settled
  (see `docs/90-Meta/vault-governance.md` § Draft / idea layer).
- Keep AGENTS/CLAUDE/rules as orchestrators; one canonical location per fact —
  no duplicated vault content in config or README.
- Game design is a decision layer peer to ADRs: research → game design
  (`docs/50-Game-Design/`, indexed by its README) → architecture (ADRs) →
  implementation. Implement gameplay only from `approved` GDDRs; an ADR must
  not contradict one; a gameplay/system change updates its GDDR in the same PR.
- On approach change: supersede, do not silently overwrite (replacement note,
  `status: superseded`, two-way `supersedes`/`superseded_by`, banner, update
  `Current-State`). Applies to ADRs and GDDRs identically.
- Update vault docs in the same PR when code changes architecture, product
  scope, gameplay, operations, or user-facing behavior.
- Session wrap-up: write/update a handoff under
  `docs/40-Execution/session-handoffs/` and update `Current-State.md`.
- Operational tracking is Linear (team FMX,
  https://linear.app/coding-x/team/FMX/active); no issues exist yet and there is
  no task-tracking process doc — agree lightweight conventions first.
- User docs are player-facing output, not authoritative implementation specs.
- MCP usage: follow `docs/90-Meta/mcp-memory-integration.md`. Allowlist is
 enforced by `.cursor/hooks/mcp-allowlist.js`. Context7 / Ref for library docs,
 Linear for ops, Figma for design, Perplexity for external research. Perplexity
 is wired via `.cursor/mcp.json` with the `perplexity-key` cloud secret so
 every cloud agent and local Cursor session discovers it automatically.
- Never store secrets, credentials, API keys, private Obsidian state, or local
  workspace state in the vault.
